Unfortunately there isn't a built-in CSS way to automatically know an element's index among its siblings. The closest CSS features would be `:nth-child()` selectors, but those can't be used in calculations.

We have a few options:

1. Use JavaScript to set the `--index` custom property on each element
2. Use a repeating gradient pattern instead of individual colors
3. Use CSS counter features (though this is more limited)

Here's how we could modify the CSS to use a repeating gradient pattern, which wouldn't require any JavaScript changes:

```css:paper-cranes/list.html
    .chip {
      /* Use repeating gradient for automatic color variation */
      background: linear-gradient(
        90deg,
        hsl(0, 85%, 90%) 0%,
        hsl(137.508, 85%, 90%) 100%
      );
      background-size: 500% 100%;
      animation: slide 40s linear infinite;
      background-position-x: calc(100% * var(--offset, 0));
      padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;
      border-radius: 0.25rem;
      box-shadow: 0 1px 2px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
      transition: filter 0.2s ease;
    }

    @keyframes slide {
      from { background-position-x: 0%; }
      to { background-position-x: 500%; }
    }
```

This would create a smoothly shifting color pattern across all chips. Each chip would get a different color based on its position in the gradient.

