Yes! We can use CSS custom properties with a CSS class that acts like a function. Here's how we can modify the CSS to create a color function based on a number input:

```css:paper-cranes/list.html
    .chip-list {
      display: flex;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      font-size: 0.8rem;
    }

    /* Color function class - takes --n as input */
    .pastel-color {
      --hue: calc(137.508deg * var(--n, 0));
      --sat: 85%;
      --light: 90%;
      background-color: hsl(var(--hue), var(--sat), var(--light));
    }

    .chip {
      padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;
      border-radius: 0.25rem;
      box-shadow: 0 1px 2px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
      transition: filter 0.2s ease;
    }

    .chip:hover {
      filter: brightness(0.95);
    }
```

Now you can use it like this in HTML:
```html
<div class="chip pastel-color" style="--n: 1">...</div>
<div class="chip pastel-color" style="--n: 2">...</div>
```

The `pastel-color` class acts like a function that takes `--n` as input and produces a unique pastel color. The golden ratio (137.508°) ensures good color distribution.

